A lot of people seem to be mixed up about Lady Gaga's makeup situation, and while she did say in an interview that Cooper made her go makeupless for the screen test, she is absolutely wearing makeup all through the actual movie. (Unless you think she somehow "naturally" turned her eyelids purple and golden and her lips bright pink and grew inch long eyelashes in some later scenes.) Whether it's on stage or behind a camera all actors or tv personalities, no matter their gender, are wearing makeup. From Lady Gaga, to Dr. Phil, to your local weather man to presidential candidates debating on national tv. If they don't then the lighting washes them out and they look like corpses. I hope this clears things up for anyone confused.

-signed a cosmetologist who has done makeup for several theatre productions

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: My personal opiniated review (WARNING FULL SPOILERS). This movie starts out great, non-linear story line, more like an indie film...really about the music; Bradley's songs sound like real legit hits and he nails acting guitar and plays solos in his own style. Gaga is just as real, musically is different style for her and folk flower child look which is cool. Then the film gradually nosedives because Gaga a la typical Britney Spears plays corny pop dressed skimpy (yawn) in full stereotype, says doesn't want to dye her hair and does, seems very contrary to character stubborn Italian NYC roots being typical Hollyweird producer puppet and Bradley just goes along with this selling out? Yeah stupid, nonsensical to character traits, and to top it off winning awards when the music sounds like crap. Then Bradley's alcoholism for some reason gets worse then for some reason Dave Chappelle just shows up, character seems forced; like hollyweird did their 5th re-write and wanted to throw another big name in the movie to sell it. Seems lame. Could have addressed the addiction issue better but by this time Bradley is constantly hanging his head down to his ankles you'd think get this mofo to a chiropractor cause he's got osteoproris. Then the typical Gaga chicanery, naked, hanging with cross dressers, the woman's personal life/carrier of  hedonistic videos, lifestyle, and satanic ceremonies (Marina Abramovic) coming thru onscreen. Whatever. 2nd/3rd acts just typical script format, wins girl, falls in love, pisses off girl, rekindles love, then Bradley.... kills himself?  Uh okay, talk about depressing. Then Gaga sings an epitaph. Boo hoo. By this time I'm fast forwarding cause the agnostic rubbish put forth is more emptiness without hope or meaning. For once how about a film with hope, meaning and the music meshing. Another script ruined by Hollyweird this had great potential stop the cookie cutter stereotypical BS and go full indy with originality, fleshed out characters and more of a message sent not contrite rubbish.

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: This movie is amazing. The storyline is great and makes you feel all kinds of emotions. But this movie also made me realize no matter how many people around you love you so much or how much money you have, you can still be broken. A lot of people don't say anything about it because they don't have the voice to. They keep it inside of them and then that leads to bad things. My heart goes to all people who are extremely depressed and feel like they don't have nothing to live for, people who feel empty inside no matter how many times they smile or laugh, people who hide themselves...who hide their emotions. People who take drugs and continuously drink alcohol/wine to forget something that has made a permanent mark in their mind. Whoever's reading this, I love you. You will get through this. Times are rough but don't ever give in. You have so much to live for...cry if you need to, but also tell someone how you're feeling. Tell someone your emotions. Don't hide them...please don't give up on yourself. I love you and I want you to be the best you as much as possible. Don't think about all the bad things. Think about all the good things that can happen in the future.‚ù§

Comment:
I hate how people love this movie, it romanticizes suicide and doesn't address the mental health issue properly, it is nothing but a trigger (without the warning by the way). Only the ones who have lost a loved one to suicide knows how much it is NOT romantic, it's just deep raw pain. This movie, although contains beautiful songs, is a disservice to people who have suicidal thoughts and people who is grieving due to suicide. 
When I watched it I didn't know anything about the movie, I watched it one week after my love killed himself, and there was no trigger warning, it completely destroyed me. 
Hollywood doesn't care, Lady Gaga or Bradley Cooper don't care either. It's 13 reasons why all over again. They just want to make money, not help people.

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
A couple of reviews (from the same person?) gave this 6/10 and stated this being a decent movie, but not Oscar¬Æ-worthy. I thought that crappy movies always get those golden statues... If I quickly think of three movies that I really like and go back to regularly have IMDb ratings as follows: 3,7; 6,1; 4,2.

If you're into ready-chewed Hollywood tripe, this movie is definitely for you. If you don't like to think for yourself and do not like any individual thoughts to be provoked inside your mind, this movie is for you then too. But if you do not want everything explained to you nor presented to you in a way so simple that an explanation isn't necessarily even needed, then this movie isn't for you. But ‚Äî again ‚Äî this is coming from a guy whose quickly-thought all-time top 3 average on IMDb is 4,67.

Apropos, a new meme review-wise on the social media/YouTube and here on IMDb seems to a "review coming from an old marine" ‚Äî as if that would really validate and give weight of significance to it. Pshaw! The rest of the world is mostly laughing at your sad attempts to bring "democracy" all over the world by bombing, destroying and murdering people ‚Äî of which majority do not have anything to do with the war that you are feeding with your politics. Or trying to use what used to be the definition of macho man par excellence ‚Äî now stripped to a sentimental, sobbing, chick-flick-watching pansy ‚Äî to promote for LGBBQTPHIVXYZ, white genocide or whatever it is that is seen profitable by the elite. USA! USA!

War is business not different from the enormous machinery of Tinseltown that must spew out products at a certain rate. This hasn't had anything to do with art for a long, long time anymore, using test screenings i.e. market research and altering the films based on them. It's just politics, mind-poisoning, propaganda and money-laundering. The same goes to pop music. It's all just industry.

And now we get to the "star" herself: Lady Gaga. Born in 1986. Marvelously, just literally out of nowhere popped into the biggest commercial fame and mainstream pop success in 2008. I repeat: out of nowhere. She is an artifact; a product. Completely artificial. There's nothing real about this character. All the stories of her artsy, underground background are just make-believe ‚Äî nothing more. If she really had been somebody in the circles of the New York scene in the 90s or early 00s, she would've been then a mere child not old enough to even have pimples on her face, let alone a prodigy dubbed as "Lady Gaga" by her peers.

Then you get the fake YouTube hits, likes, followers and subscriptions from India and China ‚Äî and the rest is history: a "star" is born, indeed. Well, she does belong to a certain group of people that control the media and entertainment. Just look at the agenda that she is so loudly promoting and sponsoring for. The gay star Bradley Cooper fits to that world of views and values better than well, just to tip you off to the right direction. She doesn't have her other eye revealed on this flick, though, but I guess everyone understood the point regardless.

"Lady Gaga is an American singer-songwriter, record producer, activist, businesswoman, fashion designer and actress." So, she is pretty much everything but a singer. That's normal these days. It's not the singing that gets these people far ‚Äî it's all the other things that are part of the trade. It would be best to call her an actor ‚Äî even though she clearly isn't too good at that either. But ‚Äî hey! ‚Äî that hasn't stopped the trophies from rolling in before.

Get out your hashtags, Twitters, Twatters and whatnots: the hype is here. Indoctrinate! Spread the word! It's cool and trendy to do so. You don't want to be different, do you? The ones who saw this at a pre-screening knew this well in advance: it's going to be a hype, because you were told it's going to be a hype. You probably even got to press a red button or a green button depending on whether you liked the ending or not.

It's all about the product placement and the propaganda ‚Äî primarily i.e. what is seen on the screen and secondarily i.e. what lies behind the production: the choice of actors etc. Art ‚Äî if there is room for any ‚Äî comes only tertiarily. Having said that:

see you at the Academy Awards¬Æ!

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
I know I'm a tad bit late. Though, in this case it's better late than never. I just saw this wonderous movie at around 6 o' clock today. It made my heart ache, it made me yearn, it made me laugh, and it made me cry. Above all else it made me fly. The scenes are effortless, the dialogue miraculous, and the actors are diamonds in the rough. I'm a hopeless romantic. However, I will say the gene has gotten a bit typical and a tad bit cookie cutter. Rest assured there is nothing mundane about this movie. It is electrifying and gravity defying. Utterly superb. There is nothing this movie can't do. It is a one man band. Watch it! It changes you. 

 I think *Shallow* and *Maybe It's Time* are the two songs that truly chronicles and heightens their relationship. The highs, lows and the straining woes.
  
*Shallow* *Jack* *Tell me Something Girl*...*Are You Happy In This Modern World?* *Or Do You Need More?* *Is There Something Else Your Looking For?* Ally is arguably legendary in her own right. Yet she's a restaurant worker by day and a dabbling musician by night. *Shallow* *Ally* *Tell Me Something Boy*... *Isn't It Hard Trying To Fill That Void?* *Or Do You Need More?* *Is There Something Else You're Searching For?* Jackson Maine is a battered and fragile shell of a man. His career is plateauing and his demons from his tultumous childhood are ever showing. He feels like the world wants so much of him and yet he's gotten so little in return. 

*Ally* *I'm Off The Deep End*.... *Watch as I dive in.* *I'll Never Meet The Ground.* *Crush Through The Surface, where they can't hurt us.* *We're Far From The Shallows Now.*

 As far as Jack is concerned he is just numb and plagued. He just doesn't care anymore. He just let's the alcohol settle the score. As far as Ally is concerned she has always been rather reserved and semi ordinary. Now she is putting herself out there. Making her gift known. She knows the full extent of her conquest and she's not looking back. 
 

Maybe it's time centers on for whom it was written. Jack. *Maine* *Maybe It's Time We Let The Old Ways Die.* x1 *It Takes A Lot To Change A Man and it takes a lot to try. *Maybe It's Time We Let The Old Ways Die.* *Nobody Knows What Waits For The Dead.* *Nobody Knows What Waits For The Dead* *They Just Believe In The Things They've Heard and The Things They've Read* *Nobody Knows What Waits For The Dead* It's telling really. In with the old, out with the new. Ally's career ultimately flourishes while Jackson's wilts. 

The death part always got to me as if you see through him and not at him I believe you can see his fate. He's acknowledging his shortcomings and transgressions to me but nonchalantly and unapologetically. It just is what it is. It is his destiny. It rocks me to my core. Hauntingly beautiful indeed. 

Lastly, as far as I'll Never Love Again goes. It's always been a tear jerker for me. Upon learning that Jackson wrote it. I begin to dissect and inspect it from his POV. Basically, I feel as though it was his cry for help. 

He is practically staying that if he can't be with Ally then he just doesn't want to be at all. It just would never be the same. He doesn't want to go on without her. He's made up his mind given the circumstances and the overall frothy reception from her camp that he is no good for Ally. She is beyond his reach. She deserves better, and he's too unpredictable and too jaded. He'll never measure up. He'll never be 100%. Like everyone else in his crappy yet eventful life she's bound to leave him. He's knows that true love and unity isn't in the cards for him the second time around. 

He doesn't want to be a mere shadow. He'll always love her but if he can't have her wholly and sincerely then he doesn't want anything. The lines * I Would Rather Wait For You,* *I'll Never Love Again,*  *Won't Let Another Day Begin* *Won't Even Let The Sunlight In* and *No other name falling off my lips* a test to that.

 All in all it was a gripping film that pulsed with vigor and with sorrow. Ally gave him a home and he drove her spark to the forefront and that ultimately led him home. All he ever wanted was to protect her innocence, nurture her creativity, protect her soul, and laminate her serenity. He just wanted her to be Ally. Stress free and restriction free. 

He wanted to be for her what no one ever was for him. A true confidant and a true friend. He just wanted to cherish and uplift her and he did up until the very end. üò™ü§ßüëè‚úç

Love and heartbreak. Pain and happiness. Ally and Jackson were us. They may have portrayed being in the 'stardom' but once the lights go off and the music dies, they're just two married couple. Two ordinary human beings who love each other and are also fighting one's demons and darkness. They embodied the two sides and faces of life- the one we see and the one we don't. The beauty and the madness, the joy and the pain.

Comment: i read so many articles how she nailed her role and how she became one geat actress. and then on the otherside (including me) there are people who are horrified by the fact that she could win an oscar. and we are not her haters, we are people who truly love good movies and we expect from the character to show its best and she just didnt. i was desperately looking for some emotions in her, some charisma, something, ANYTHING but for the love of God didnt found anything. all i could see was one big P.R, for her and nothing more. Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
üí´ I took my kids to see "A Star Is Born" the other night, & I must confess; this iconic love story about star-crossed lovers & their tragically misaligned career-trajectories invoked a wee degree of existential rumination in me. 
Bradley Cooper plays a whisky voiced country-rock star by the name of Jordan Maine whose comet has begun to wane. Lady Ga Ga plays Allie, a diffident waitress whose talents remain mere smolderings until that chance encounter--Jordan, searching for a place to drink, stumbles onto Allie's breathtaking cabaret performance in a drag bar. 
I've seen three other variations on this plot, but this one far exceeds its progenitors. There's much I could say about this version of "A Star Is Born," but for the sake of brevity, I'm just going to focus on how this movie seems to mirror today's cultural zeitgeist. 
This movie trailer I posted opens up with my favorite song from the film, "Maybe It's Time to Let the Old Ways Die." Maine keeps coming back to this folksy country ballad as it seems like an important statement of theme & purpose for the story; the song's not only an exploration of what's actually happening when this grizzled crooner plucks young Allie out of obscurity, but on a larger scale, the elegiac lyrics also seem to reflect some kind of protracted extinction of the 'old-white-guy' & everything this demographic may have once stood for:
"üéº Maybe it's time to let the old ways die/It takes a lot to change a man/Hell, it takes a lot to try/Maybe it's time to let the old ways die/Nobody knows what awaits for the dead..."
I hope I'm not spoiling the ending for anybody here, but considering how the protagonist has killed himself in each of the 3 previous Hollywood versions, I imagine y'all have gotten the memo on this one. 
'Purposelessness' leads to suicide, & being a proponent of logo-therapy, I'm always trying to motivate my students to find a purpose in life or as the French call it, a 'raison d'etre.' Without a sense of purpose, depression naturally sets in, & it's obvious that Jackson Maine is indeed depressed. Atop of all his issues that he numbs with alcohol, he also recognizes that his gritty style of music is about ready for the glue factory. & to make matters worse, he's losing his hearing & pondering whether or not he's ready for the glue factory, himself...
84% of people who kill themselves are white & about 77% are men. You could say the character Jordan Maine is the poster-boy for these stats. 
All in all, I think men are their own worst enemies. They tend not to openly discuss their feelings. Jordan Maine had an opportunity to talk about his insecurities with Allie as they lay in bed before her big show, yet he chose to keep the conversation laconic while masking his core depression with a spurious smile.
I can't help but to imagine that if he'd been more forthcoming about how badly he felt for having sullied Allie's public-image with much of his self-destructive alcoholism, that they could have found another resolution other than suicide...
Anyhow, I didn't cry. I wanted to--mainly because this particular issue haunts me till this very day. But I didn't want to appear to be a wuss in front of my girls. 
& I suppose that's the crux of the problem right there... 
Maybe it‚Äôs time to let the old ways die.
üé¨ Bottom line, this movie gets a strong thumbs up from this ol' cowboy. üëçüèº

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: I remember the critical reaction to the 1976 version of this movie; Streisand was brutally mauled for making a "vanity film".  She was egomaniacal.  She gave herself too many close-ups.  She was out of place in the rock world.  All of which is pretty outrageous when you compare it to this latest version.  Bradley Cooper has taken this classic melodrama - which is called A Star Is Born and has, in all previous versions, been about just that: a rising star - and made it predominantly a story of addiction, self-destruction and male angst.  In other words: he has totally reversed the dynamic of the movie and made it mostly about his character, downgrading the rising star aspect of the story in the process.  He gives himself more screen time than his co-star (and way more than any of the previous actors playing his role).  He adds characters (like his brother) and backstory, that make the story more about Jackson Maine than about Ally (who, please note, doesn't even warrant a second name).  And he makes it an overwhelmingly male film.  Ally's only "female" friends are drag queens!  Cooper even manages to make himself look good, even while playing drunk and dishevelled, while stripping Gaga of all make-up (which makes her look plain) for half the film, then cursing her with a star makeover that makes her look like one of her drag queen friends.  But where Streisand was lambasted for being narcissistic and egomaniacal, Cooper is being hailed for his direction and performance.  Talk about double standards.

I‚Äôm getting sick of seeing this new narrative that‚Äôs being pushed that Lady Gaga had to overcome soooo much and struggled. Not only is she a TV star,but is about to be a movie star with a movie once again pushing her character as a girl that is being held down by the establishment. 

The scene in the trailer shows her talking about how her nose is ‚Äútoo big‚Äù for her to be a star... clearly this is trying to reference her in real life,not just the character in the movie,and trying to garner sympathy for her. There‚Äôs absolutely nothing to be sympathetic to this woman about- this is not due to hatred towards her. It‚Äôs just I can‚Äôt stand seeing someone who has had so much success(and is there anyone out there who is holding her down because of her looks?..most people praise her as attractive) being portrayed as someone who has been held down,or had to rise above so many obstacles... give me a fucking break. 

 If you‚Äôre a fan of hers,fine...but that doesn‚Äôt make this kind of bullshit any less bullshit.  you don‚Äôt have to be held down or someone who had to rise above your circumstances to be loved and appreciated. This woman has had almost nothing but success,especially when you compare her to the average person. Does this movie speak to the  average looking woman being made to feel beautiful in the outside as they are in the inside. I have noticed the inner geek, outcast, great personality, being the leading actress in almost all teen movies, chic flicks, and it is just not real so they live vicariously through these movies that tell the average or below average looking girl they too can have their prince charming, who is also a lost soul and the girl sticking by his side no matter at what cost, YUCK! Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: "A Star is born" will always be remembered for the voice and interpretation of Barbra Streisand and luckily did not try to re-edit the second Version. Lady Gaga's Voice arrangements were absolutely beautiful, touching and moving as they should be. this is a new version and we have to forget who watched any of the first 2 versions and focus on the chemistry of Gaga and Cooper. I loved every song released so far and I can't wait to buy the Soundtrack. Singing only Gaga already deserves to be rewarded and I believe that her performance will be passionate, poignant, strong and in a certain way Delicate. Gaga is much better at actually interpreting real songs and escaping from that silly pop with which she launched herself to Stardom. In "Joanne" she has demonstrated that it can go much further and now with this trail we know that really "A star is born". Hoping she wins many prizes with her performance, without forgetting Cooper who is simply perfect in her role, it seems that it was written to match exactly with the personality he created for the character in the Film. I highly recommend the film and note 10 for everyone involved.

Comment:
I found this film brilliant, blown away in fact at the music too, it was so well done. I have seen a wonderful side of Bradley Cooper in this film and have huge respect for him as a result; you'd almost fall in love with his character, I'd love a partner like that, I really would, minus the addiction of course.. 

He is amazing in this film, Lady Gaga was fantastic too. Good love story... I was so surprised Bradley Cooper could sing so well, cannot praise him or this film enough... The end killed me because I have had someone in my own life who tried to take their life on a couple of occasions, so I must say I cried the whole way home in the car after the cinema... 

Truly loved this film, it will stay with me for a good while and will probably go to see it again!

Did anyone notice after seeing this movie that in the very beginning, right before the title of the movie unfolds, Gaga sings "when all the world is a hopeless jumble and the raindrops tumble all around...". That's the first time we hear her sing.

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
Bradley Cooper, the  Directors Eye you poses is a true gift my friend.  The beautifully captured and measured nuance you were able to render brought me inside of the movie.  For the first time since 1999 i was transported into an experience while watching a movie.  You and your cast took me on a roller coaster of emotion.  I believed you were Jackson.  The authentic and naked delivery of Lady Gaga‚Äôs performance when coming on stage with Jackson for the first time made the hair on my arms stand up it was so electrifying.  The on screen chemistry was able to successfully weave a romantic tapestry that was later used to show the frayed edges that would be prayed upon.  

The moment in the film that is one of the most powerful i have ever seen in a movie, is the conversation between Bobby and Jackson in the driveway when he is dropping him off.  I was blown away at how you and your cast were able to render such powerful and emotionally charged seconds on screen that made me have to hold back my own tears.  I lived inside of that moment with Bobby and Jackson from both of their perspectives.  

If i had any criticisms for this movie, it would be that the initial romance happens very quickly, but because of the effective eye of director, it was pulled off successfully.

Lastly, I could appreciate how you used a very diplomatic approach in addressing the shortcomings in the music industry by pruning the tree instead of chopping it down.

Thank you all for a beautiful experience!

- V√èNT√ìRY BLAKE MAGNUM MOORE

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: My normal genre is listening to hard rock and the like...but after catching Lady Gaga in American Horror Story and thoroughly enjoying watching her act, and then opening myself up to hear her sing, and then finally watching this movie trailer...I have to say that this woman is one of the most beautiful, talented, and amazing ladies that I have ever seen...and her singing makes my eyes water up every time I hear her songs. Lady Gaga has such incredible talent; and I'm honestly mesmerized by her performances. Heaven has a special place for Lady Gaga. Stefani is truly a class act; and if her heart is as genuine on the inside, as what you can see and hear from her performances on both film or stage, then she is truly an angel on this earth. I feel like many good actors/actresses can project a piece of their inner-selves into their performances, and if this is the same for Lady Gaga, then she is perhaps one of the most honest and amazing stars that have ever existed. Normally I never offer-up these compliments to anyone, let alone a pop star or actress because I'm not a person who like to idolize others, but my God, Stefani has such incredible talent. I grew up with a father who made his entire living as a musician and guitar teacher, and I've been singing and playing guitar my whole life so far...and I sometimes just daydream that I could actually jam out with Lady Gaga. That would definitely be a bucket-list wish if I could ever have the honor of meeting Lady Gaga. I learned about Lady Gaga's past from what she's told others about growing up and getting discovered; and I hope that maybe one day I too can get recognized as well. Who knows; maybe if I got my name out there and I was big enough, I could talk Lady Gaga into doing some music together (a guy can dream, right? haha) There's obviously a reason why Lady Gaga has become so incredibly famous (because her talent deserves it)...but for someone like me who usually has your normal "guy" tastes in hard rock or action films and whatnot...I will always pause to hear or watch Lady Gaga act, sing, or speak. Lady Gaga's fiance is an incredibly lucky man for being in the presence of an angel; and I hope he always treats her like the queen that she is.

Comment: Calling the 1976 version a blockbuster is an understatement. First of all, any new Barbra Streisand project was an "event" of epic proportion. Add to the fact that she was already THE most successful actress as well as THE most successful female recording artist of the entire decade when A Star is Born came out (Christmas Day 1976), and of course having Evergreen reach number #1 only sealed the deal. Yes, the critics ripped it to shreds, but it didn't matter, because people were going to see Barbra Streisand in concert on the big screen (over and over and over again), and that's all that mattered. It's hard to imagine this new version even coming close ... and of course, it won't.   Bradley Cooper was ALL WRONG for this role.  Big mistake.

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
This Hollywood classic has been made *three times* , in three very different movie industry eras: in 1937, 1954 and 1976. The _last version_ was with Barbra Streisand and Kris Kristofferson, which had won 4 Academy awards and 5 Golden Globe awards. Bradley Cooper's version will be the 4th _remake_ version. Let's see how it will compare to the previous 3 versions and how many Awards it will receive. Choosing *Gaga* as the leading lady was an excellent choice; she has proven herself to be a good actress - and as we all know : is a phenomenal singer and can definitely stand up to _Streisand_ as far as her *vocal range* is concerned.  
*OCTOBER IS COMING* ............

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: At 2:00 to 2:02 (the part showing the "Lady Gaga" caption), you will hear the D/F# chord, which is a first-inversion dominant major chord prominently placed in that moment of the song, resolving nicely to the next chord (G Major, the tonic chord) with Lady Gaga still singing over it. Chords like that, widely used in classical music, that's placed inside a supposedly simple country tune, are typically the trademark chords of musicians with a classical music background, such as Lady Gaga. The inverted chord also creates the "awe" or "uplifting" sound effect.

And Bradley's always been good in my books (and hot!), and now we know he can sing too!  I've love to agree with other commenters about this getting awards, but I don't trust the industry to actually award good work.  I've sat through stupid award shows too many times, only to be disappointed by the actual winners.  If I love a movie, actor, etc...they don't win.  I sat through the damn awards a few months ago hoping The Greatest Showman music would win, only to swear at the tv when it didn't.  I do hope this movie has better luck!

Title: A STAR IS BORN - Official Trailer 1
Comment: As a Streisand fan who saw the '76 version in theaters, this version with Gaga rings the most true from what I can tell. I can totally buy Gaga as this character. She's never hid her rock/country leanings since the beginning and she started as a song writer. For many,myself included, it was hard to buy Barbra in the role of a lounge act who would steal rock fans away from Kristofferson. It was still an exciting,albeit tacky, movie cause it was Barbra in her prime but it was a movie very much of its time. It went perfectly with swag lamps and shag rugs. I can't wait to see what Bradley Cooper has done with the story. It looks much more down to earth so far.
